Single-variable plots in R

library(tidyverse) # loads ggplot2

In this vid, weâll use the diamonds data set to practice single-variable plots using the ggplot function.

One categorical variable

The go-to plot for a single categorical variable is the bar chart.

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = cut)) +
  geom_bar()

Adding color:

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = cut)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "limegreen",
           color = "darkgreen") +
  theme_minimal()

Reverse the orientation:

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(y = cut)) +
  geom_bar(fill = "limegreen",
           color = "darkgreen") +
  theme_minimal()

Order the factor levels by frequency:

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = fct_infreq(cut))) +
  geom_bar(fill = "limegreen",
           color = "darkgreen") +
  theme_minimal()

Fix labels:

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = fct_infreq(cut))) +
  geom_bar(fill = "limegreen",
           color = "darkgreen") +
  labs(x = "Cut",
       y = "Count",
       title = "Fair cut diamonds are rare") +
  theme_minimal()

See my vid on pie charts here. Use them with extreme care!

One quantitative variable

The go-to plot for a single quantitative variable is the histogram.

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = price)) +
  geom_histogram()
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value `binwidth`.

Change the number of bins:

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = price)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 1000,
                 boundary = 0) + # or bins 
  theme_minimal()

Change to a frequency polygon:

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = price)) +
  geom_freqpoly(binwidth = 1000, 
                 boundary = 0) +
  theme_minimal()

A density plot:

theme_set(theme_minimal())

ggplot(diamonds,
       aes(x = price)) +
  geom_density(fill = "#5798A6",
               linewidth = .2)

For very small data sets, you can also consider geom_dotplot.
